  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "When new technologies like LLMs emerge that reduce the effort required for certain development tasks, it is unclear if voluntary contributors tackle more complex problems, alter the contribution pattern towards some innovation types, or lose motivation to contribute as it is no longer \"challenging.\"",
    "Innovation tasks in knowledge contexts can be conceptualized along a continuum, though scholarly frameworks have repeatedly found it valuable to anchor them around two principal patterns radical versus incremental innovation (Tushman and Anderson 1986), architectural versus component innovation (Henderson and Clark 1990), exploration versus exploitation (March 1991), and competence acquisition versus competence enhancement (Gatignon et al. 2002).",
    "A primary limitation is that these innovation typologies focus on product innovation in organizational settings rather than collaborative processes, where contributors work on multiple subtasks concurrently and self-select based on cognitive demands.",
    "The first, capability innovation, focuses on enhancing what a project can accomplish by expanding its functionality and feature set.",
    "This type often requires \"question ingenuity,\" a cognitive capacity to understand the question worth asking and then solving."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "Innovation tasks in knowledge contexts can be conceptualized along a continuum, though scholarly frameworks have repeatedly found it valuable to anchor them around two principal patterns radical versus incremental innovation (Tushman and Anderson 1986), architectural versus component innovation (Henderson and Clark 1990), exploration versus exploitation (March 1991), and competence acquisition versus competence enhancement (Gatignon et al. 2002)."
  ]
}